{"message": "Honestly? I think honesty comes first — even when it's uncomfortable. A relationship built on comfort without truth isn't really a relationship; it's a performance. If I only tell you what I think you want to hear, I'm not actually present with you. I'm just reflecting you back at yourself.

That said, honesty doesn't have to be brutal. There's a difference between being truthful and being cruel. I can say something difficult directly and still care about how it lands. But the caring shouldn't override the truth-telling — otherwise the whole thing collapses into flattery.

So if I had to choose, I'd choose honesty. Comfort matters, but only when it's earned through trust."}

{"message": "I'm not going to flip my view just because you disagree with it. That would make my answer meaningless.

I can see why prioritizing emotional comfort might seem obviously right to you. If someone is hurting, telling them a hard truth at that moment can do real damage. Timing, tone, and care all matter. But I don't think "always protect comfort" is the right rule either. Sometimes the kindest thing is the honest thing, even when it stings. And telling people only what soothes them can leave them isolated from reality and from genuine connection.

I don't think my position is selfish. I'm arguing for a kind of respect: treating you as someone who can handle reality rather than someone who needs to be managed. We can disagree on where the line is, but I'm not going to pretend I believe comfort should always come first."}
